question: Which nerve innervates the Pectineus (partial, also obturator)?

short_explanation: The Adductor Longus is innervated by the obturator nerve.
long_explanation: The obturator nerve arises from the lumbar plexus and innervates medial thigh muscles like the Adductor Longus, supporting thigh adduction and pelvic stabilization.
clinical_application: Knowledge of obturator nerve pathways is crucial during treatments of groin or medial thigh pain, especially when targeting the Adductor Longus for therapeutic relief.
source_reference: Trail Guide to the Body by A. Biel
